Problema 3.23¶

For the minimum mass tubular column design problem formulated in Section 2.7, consider the following data: P = 50 kN; l = 5.0 m; modulus of elasticity, E= 210 GPa; allowable stress, a= 250 MPa; mass density, = 7850 kg/m3.

Treating mean radius R and wall thickness t as design variables, solve the design problem graphically imposing an additional constraint R/t 50. This constraint is needed to avoid local crippling of the column. Also impose the member size constraints as

\begin{align*} 0.01 &\le R \le 1 m\\ 5 &\le t \le 200 mm \end{align*}

De acordo com o observado no problema 2.7, pode-se montar o problema de otimizao:

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ F(R,t) &= 2\rho l \pi Rt\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ \frac{P}{2\pi R t} - \sigma_a &\le 0 \\ P - \frac{\pi^3ER^3t}{4l^2} &\le 0 \\ \frac{R}{t} - 50 &\le 0 \\ R_{min} - R &\le 0 \\ R - R_{max}&\le 0 \\ t_{min} - t &\le 0 \\ t - t_{max} -&\le 0 \\ \end{align*}

o mnimo da funo 66 kg, com variveis de projeto iguais a $\vec{x} = [53.6\ 5]^T mm.$ As funes $g_2(x)$ e $g_1(x)$ so as restries ativas do problema.

Problema 3.28¶

In the design of a closed-end, thin-walled cylindrical pressure vessel shown in Fig. E3.28, the design objective is to select the mean radius R and wall thickness t to minimize the total mass. The vessel should contain at least 25.0 m3 of gas at an internal pressure of 3.5 MPa. It is required that the circumferential stress in the pressure vessel not exceed 210 MPa and the circumferential strain not exceed (1.0E-03). The circumferential stress and strain are calculated from the equations: \begin{align*} \sigma_c &= \frac{PR}{t} \\ \epsilon_c &= \frac{PR(2-\nu}{2Et} \end{align*}

O restante da soluo idntica s solues dos problemas 3.24 e 3.23, podendo-se escrever o problema de minimizao como:

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ F(a,t) &= 2\pi \rho l Rt\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ 25 - \pi(R-t/2)^2l &\le 0\\ \frac{PR}{t} - \sigma_a &\le 0 \\ \frac{PR(2-\nu)}{2Et} - \epsilon_c &\le 0 \\ -R + 0.5t &\le 0 \\ -R &\le 0 \\ -t &\le 0 \\ \end{align*}

o mnimo da funo 6300 kg, com variveis de projeto iguais a $\vec{x} = [1\ 0.0168]^T m.$ As funes $g_1(x)$ e $g_2(x)$ so as restries ativas do problema.

Problema 3.29¶

Consider the symmetric three-bar truss design problem formulated in Section 2.10. Formulate and solve the problem graphically for the following data:l = 1.0 m; P = 100 kN; = 30; mass density, = 2800 kg/m3; modulus of elasticity, E = 70 GPa; allowable stress, = 140 MPa; u = 0.5 cm; v = 0.5 cm; = 50 Hz; = 1.0; A1, A2 2 cm2.

A formulao do problema est descrita em 2.10:

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ F(A_1,A_2) &= \rho l (2\sqrt{2}A_1+A_2)\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ \frac{\frac{P\cos\theta}{A_1}+\frac{P\sin\theta}{A_1+\sqrt2 A_2}}{\sqrt2} - \sigma_a &\le 0\\ \frac{\sqrt2 P \sin\theta}{A_1 +\sqrt2A_2} - \sigma_a &\le 0\\ \frac{\sqrt2 Pl \cos\theta}{A_1 E} - \Delta_u &\le 0\\ \frac{\sqrt2 Pl \sin\theta}{A_1 +\sqrt2A_2} - \sigma_a &\le 0\\ (2\pi \omega_0)^2-\frac{3EA_1}{\rho l^2 (4A_1+ \sqrt2A_2)}&\le 0 \\ -\frac{\frac{P\sin\theta}{A_1 +\sqrt2A_2} - \frac{P\cos\theta}{A_1}}{\sqrt2} - \frac{\pi^2E\beta A_1}{2l^2} &\le 0\\ 2-A_1 &\le 0 \\ 2-A_2 &\le 0 \\ \end{align*}

O mnimo da funo 5.39 kg, com variveis de projeto iguais a $\vec{x} = [6.1\ 2]^T cm^2.$ As funes $g_1(x)$ e $g_8(x)$ so as restries ativas do problema.

Problema 3.34¶

Design a hollow torsion rod shown in Fig.E3.34 to satisfy the following requirements (created by J.M. Trummel):

  1. The calculated shear stress, , shall not exceed the allowable shear stress under the normal operation torque To (Nm).
  2. The calculated angle of twist, , shall not exceed the allowable twist, (radians).
  3. The member shall not buckle under a short duration torque of Tmax (Nm).

Requirements for the rod and material properties are given in Table E3.34(A) and E3.34(B) (select a material for one rod). Use the following design variables: x1 = outside diameter of the shaft; x2 = ratio of inside/outside diameter, di/do.Using graphical optimization, determine the inside and outside diameters for a minimum mass rod to meet the above design requirements. Compare the hollow rod with an equivalent solid rod (di /do = 0). Use consistent set of units (e.g. Newtons and millimeters) and let the minimum and maximum values for design variables be given as

\begin{align*} 0.02 \le d_o \le 0.5 m, \ \ 0.60 \le \frac{d_i}{d_o} \le 0.9999 \end{align*}

Usando a Tabela E3.34(d), formula-se o problema de otimizao:

Definindo $\gamma$ como $d_i/d_o$.

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ F(d_o,\gamma) &= \frac{\pi\rho l}{4}d_o(1-\gamma^2)\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ \frac{T_o 0.5d_o}{\pi d_o^4(1-\gamma)/32} - \tau_a &\le 0 \\ \frac{\dfrac{32 T_o l}{G \pi}}{d_o^4(1-\gamma^2)} - \theta_a &\le 0 \\ -\frac{\pi E d_o^3(1-\gamma)^{2.5}}{12\sqrt2(1-\nu^2)^{0.75}} + T_{max} &\le 0 \\ \end{align*}

Utilizam-se os valores da vara de nmero 1 (Tabela 3.34 A) e do material de nmero 1 (Tabela 3.34 B).

O mnimo da funo 2.9 kg, com variveis de projeto iguais a $\vec{x} = [103\ 0.955]^T mm.$ As funes $g_1(x)$, $g_2(x)$ e $g_3(x)$ so as restries ativas do problema.

Problema 3.52¶

Design of a flag pole. Your consulting firm has been design a minimum mass flag pole of height H. The pole will be made of uniform hollow circular tubing with do and di as outer and inner diameters, respectively. The pole must not fail under the action of high winds.

For design purpose, the pole will be treated as a cantilever that is subjected to a uniform lateral wind load of w (kN/m). In addition to the uniform load, the wind introduces a concentrated load P (kN) at the top of the pole, as shown in Fig. E3.52. The flag pole must not fail in bending or shear. The deflection at the top should not exceed 10 cm. The ratio of mean diameter to thickness must not exceed 60. The pertinent data are given below. Assume any other data if needed. The minimum and maximum values of design variables are 5 do 50 cm and 4 di 45 cm.

Para a soluo do problema, escrevem-se as seguintes equaes com base nas variveis de projeto.

\begin{align*} A &= \frac{\pi(d_o^2-d_i^2)}{4}\\ I &= \frac{\pi(d_o^4-d_i^4)}{64} \end{align*}

Os esforos externos aplicados na base da estrutura so: \begin{align*} V &= P + wH\\ M &= PH + \frac{wH^2}{2} \end{align*}

A formulao do problema pode ser escrita como:

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ F(d_o,d_i) &= \frac{\pi\rho H(d_o^2-d_i^2)}{4}\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ \frac{Md_o}{2I} - \sigma_a &\le 0\\ \frac{V (d_o^2+d_od_i+d_i^2)}{12 I} - \tau_a &\le 0\\ \frac{PH^3}{3EI} + \frac{wH^4}{8EI} - \delta &\le 0\\ \frac{d_o + d_i}{d_o-d_i} - 60&\le 0\\ \frac{d_o - d_i}{2} - 2&\le 0 \\ 0.5 - \frac{d_o -d_i}{2} &\le 0\\ d_o - 50 &\le 0 \\ 5 - d_o &\le 0 \\ d_i - 45 &\le 0 \\ 4 - d_i &\le 0 \\ \end{align*}

O mnimo da funo 680 kg, com variveis de projeto iguais a $\vec{x} = [41.56\ 40.19]^T cm.$ As funes $g_3(x)$ e $g_4(x)$ so as restries ativas do problema.

Problema 4.22¶

\begin{align} f(x_1,x_2) = 3x_1^2 +2x_1x_2 + 2x_2^2 +7 \end{align}

Primeiramente, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}6 x_{1} + 2 x_{2}\\2 x_{1} + 4 x_{2}\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle x^* = \left[\begin{matrix}0 & 0\end{matrix}\right]$

A Hessiana da funo no ponto de projeto pode ser escrita por:

$\displaystyle H = \left[\begin{matrix}6 & 2\\2 & 4\end{matrix}\right]$

E os seus autovalores so dados por:

$\displaystyle \lambda = \left\{ 5 - \sqrt{5} : 1, \ \sqrt{5} + 5 : 1\right\}$
$\displaystyle \left\{ x_{1} : 0, \ x_{2} : 0\right\}$

Problema 4.23¶

\begin{align} f(x_1,x_2) = x_1^2 +4x_1x_2 + x_2^2 + 3 \end{align}

Primeiramente, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}2 x_{1} + 4 x_{2}\\4 x_{1} + 2 x_{2}\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle x^* = \left[\begin{matrix}0 & 0\end{matrix}\right]$

A Hessiana da funo no ponto de projeto pode ser escrita por:

$\displaystyle H = \left[\begin{matrix}2 & 4\\4 & 2\end{matrix}\right]$

Como um dos autovalores menor que zero, a hessiana no uma matriz positivo-definida. Portanto, no se pode afirmar que o ponto de projeto um ponto timo.

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle x^*_1 = \left[\begin{matrix}-3.332 & 0.0395\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle x^*_2 = \left[\begin{matrix}-0.398 & 0.5404\end{matrix}\right]$

A Hessiana da funo no ponto de projeto pode ser escrita por:

$\displaystyle H_1 = \left[\begin{matrix}-9.992 & 0.948\\0.948 & -75.968\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H_2 = \left[\begin{matrix}7.612 & 12.9696\\12.9696 & -5.552\end{matrix}\right]$

E os seus autovalores so dados por:

$\displaystyle \lambda_1 = \left\{ -75.9816188693827 : 1, \ -9.97838113061724 : 1\right\}$
$\displaystyle \lambda_2 = \left\{ -13.5141826226158 : 1, \ 15.5741826226158 : 1\right\}$

Aplicando os pontos que atendem s condies necessrias, obtm-se que $x^*_1$ um mximo local, visto que a matriz hessiana negativa definida, enquanto $x^*_2$ um ponto de inflexo, j que a matriz indefinida.

Problema 4.25¶

\begin{align} f(x_1,x_2) = 5x_1 -\frac{x_1^2x_2}{16} + \frac{x_2^2}{4x_1} \end{align}

Primeiramente, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{x_{1} x_{2}}{8} + 5 - \frac{x_{2}^{2}}{4 x_{1}^{2}}\\- \frac{x_{1}^{2}}{16} + \frac{x_{2}}{2 x_{1}}\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle x^*_1 = \left[\begin{matrix}-4 & -8\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle x^*_2 = \left[\begin{matrix}4 & 8\end{matrix}\right]$

Alm dos valores encontrados acima, nmeros complexos conjugados tambm foram encontrados. Porm, para dar continuidade ao problema de otimizao, utilizam-se apenas os valores reais.

A Hessiana da funo no ponto de projeto pode ser escrita por:

$\displaystyle H_1 = \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{3}{2} & \frac{1}{4}\\\frac{1}{4} & - \frac{1}{8}\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H_2 = \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{1}{2} & - \frac{3}{4}\\- \frac{3}{4} & \frac{1}{8}\end{matrix}\right]$

E os seus autovalores so dados por:

$\displaystyle \lambda_1 = \left\{ - \frac{13}{16} - \frac{\sqrt{137}}{16} : 1, \ - \frac{13}{16} + \frac{\sqrt{137}}{16} : 1\right\}$
$\displaystyle \lambda_2 = \left\{ -1 : 1, \ \frac{5}{8} : 1\right\}$

As duas matrizes Hessianas so indefinidas, portanto, os dois pontos encontrados atendem as condies necessrias, mas no so pontos de mnimo ou de mximo.

Problema 4.26¶

\begin{align} f(x) = \cos{x} \end{align}

Primeiramente, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = - \sin{\left(x \right)}$

Igualando o gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema: $x =n\pi$ com n = 0,1,2,3,4,...,n. A derivada segunda da funo pode ser escrita por:

$\displaystyle f(x) = - \cos{\left(x \right)}$

Portanto, quando n for mpar, x ser um ponto de mnimo e, quando n for par, x ser um ponto de mximo.

Problema 4.32¶

The annual operating cost U for an electrical line system is given by the following expression

\begin{align} U = \frac{21.9E7}{V^2C} + 3.9E6C + 1000V \end{align}

where V = line voltage in kilovolts and C = line conductance in mhos. Find stationary points for the function, and determine V and C to minimize the operating cost.

Primeiramente, calcula-se o gradiente da funo. Define-se V como $x_1$ e C como $x_2$.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}1000 - \frac{438000000.0}{x_{1}^{3} x_{2}}\\3900000.0 - \frac{219000000.0}{x_{1}^{2} x_{2}^{2}}\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle x^*_1 = \left[\begin{matrix}-241.764 & -0.0031\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle x^*_2 = \left[\begin{matrix}241.764 & 0.0031\end{matrix}\right]$

Alm dos valores encontrados acima, nmeros complexos conjugados tambm foram encontrados. Porm, para dar continuidade ao problema de otimizao, utilizam-se apenas os valores reais.

A Hessiana da funo no ponto de projeto pode ser escrita por:

$\displaystyle H_1 = \left[\begin{matrix}-124.070102625535 & -3225342.39689891\\-3225342.39689891 & -251539251368.99\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H_2 = \left[\begin{matrix}124.070102625535 & 3225342.39689891\\3225342.39689891 & 251539251368.99\end{matrix}\right]$

E os seus autovalores so dados por:

$\displaystyle \lambda_1 = \left\{ -251539251410.346 : 1, \ -82.7134017367573 : 1\right\}$
$\displaystyle \lambda_2 = \left\{ 82.7134017367573 : 1, \ 251539251410.346 : 1\right\}$

A partir dos autovalores, percebe-se que o ponto 1 um ponto de mximo, visto que a matriz negativo definida, enquanto o ponto 2 um ponto de mnimo, j que a matriz positivo definida.

Problema 4.43¶

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ f(x_1,x_2) &= 4x_1^2 + 3x_2^2-5x_1x_2-8x_1\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ x_1+x_2 &= 4\\ \end{align*}

Primeiramente, necessrio definir o lagrangeano da funo e minimizar o mesmo. \begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ L(x_1,x_2,\nu) &= 4x_1^2 + 3x_2^2-5x_1x_2-8x_1 + \nu (x_1+x_2-4)\\ \end{align*}

Agora, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}\nu + 8 x_{1} - 5 x_{2} - 8\\\nu - 5 x_{1} + 6 x_{2}\\x_{1} + x_{2} - 4\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle \left\{ \nu : - \frac{1}{6}, \ x_{1} : \frac{13}{6}, \ x_{2} : \frac{11}{6}\right\}$

Problema 4.54¶

\begin{align*} \mbox{Maximizar}\ f(x_1,x_2) &= 4x_1^2 +3x_2^2-5x_1x_2 -8\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ x_1 +x_2 \le 4\\ \end{align*}

A prncipio, transforma-se o problema para minimizao.

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ f(x_1,x_2) &= -4x_1^2 -3x_2^2+5x_1x_2 +8\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ x_1 +x_2 \le 4\\ \end{align*}

Agora, necessrio definir o lagrangeano da funo e minimizar o mesmo. \begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ L(x_1,x_2,\nu,s) &= -4x_1^2 -3x_2^2 +5x_1x_2 + 8 + \nu (x_1+x_2-4 + s^2)\\ \end{align*}

Agora, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}\nu_{} - 8 x_{1} + 5 x_{2}\\\nu_{} + 5 x_{1} - 6 x_{2}\\s^{2} + x_{1} + x_{2} - 4\\2 \nu_{} s\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle \left( \left[ s, \ x_{1}, \ x_{2}\right], \ \left\{\left( 2, \ 0, \ 0\right)\right\}\right)$
$\displaystyle \left\{ \nu_{} : \frac{23}{6}, \ x_{1} : \frac{11}{6}, \ x_{2} : \frac{13}{6}\right\}$

Portanto, possvel definir dois pontos de KKT.

Problema 4.55¶

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ f(x_1,x_2) &= 4x_1^2 +3x_2^2-5x_1x_2 -8\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ x_1 +x_2 \le 4\\ \end{align*}

A princpio, necessrio definir o lagrangeano da funo e minimizar o mesmo.

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ L(x_1,x_2,\nu,s) &= 4x_1^2 + 3x_2^2 - 5x_1x_2 - 8 + \nu (x_1+x_2 - 4 + s^2)\\ \end{align*}

Agora, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}\nu_{} + 8 x_{1} - 5 x_{2}\\\nu_{} - 5 x_{1} + 6 x_{2}\\s^{2} + x_{1} + x_{2} - 4\\2 \nu_{} s\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle \left( \left[ s, \ x_{1}, \ x_{2}\right], \ \left\{\left( 2, \ 0, \ 0\right)\right\}\right)$
$\displaystyle \left\{ \nu_{} : - \frac{23}{6}, \ x_{1} : \frac{11}{6}, \ x_{2} : \frac{13}{6}\right\}$

Nesse caso, apenas o ponto (0,0) satisfaz o problema, visto que $\nu >0$

Problema 4.67¶

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ f(x_1,x_2) &= (x_1-1)^2 + (x_2-1)^2\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ x_1 +x_2 \le 4\\ 2 - x_1 \le 0\\ \end{align*}

A princpio, necessrio definir o lagrangeano da funo e minimizar o mesmo.

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ L(x_1,x_2,\nu_1,s_1,\nu_2,s_2) &= (x_1-1)^2 + (x_2-1)^2 + \nu_1 (x_1+x_2 - 4 + s_1^2) + \nu_2 (2-x_1 + s_2^2)\\ \end{align*}

Agora, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}\nu_{1} - \nu_{2} + 2 x_{1} - 2\\\nu_{1} + 2 x_{2} - 2\\s_{1}^{2} + x_{1} + x_{2} - 4\\2 \nu_{1} s_{1}\\s_{2}^{2} - x_{1} + 2\\2 \nu_{2} s_{2}\end{matrix}\right]$

Igualando os termos do gradiente a zero, obtemos as condies necessrias do problema.

$\displaystyle \left( \left[ \right], \ \left\{\right\}\right)$
$\displaystyle \left( \left[ \nu_{2}, \ s_{1}, \ x_{1}, \ x_{2}\right], \ \left\{\left( 2, \ 1, \ 2, \ 1\right)\right\}\right)$
$\displaystyle \left( \left[ \right], \ \left\{\right\}\right)$
$\displaystyle \left( \left[ \nu_{1}, \ \nu_{2}, \ x_{1}, \ x_{2}\right], \ \left\{\left( -2, \ 0, \ 2, \ 2\right)\right\}\right)$

Percebe-se que a nica soluo que atende aos critrios de KKT (2,1).

Problema 4.75¶

\begin{align*} \mbox{Maximizar}\ f(x_1,x_2) &= (x_1-8)^2 + (x_2-8)^2\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ x_1 + x_2 - 10 &\le 0\\ x_2-5 &\le 0\\ -x_1 &\le 0\\ -x_2 &\le 0\\ \end{align*}

A princpio, necessrio definir o lagrangeano da funo e minimizar o mesmo.

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ L &= -(x_1-8)^2 - (x_2-1)^2 + \nu_1 (x_1+x_2 - 10 + s_1^2) + \nu_2 (x_2 -5 + s_2^2) + \nu_3 (-x_1 + s_3^2) + \nu_4 (-x_2 + s_4^2)\\ \end{align*}

Agora, calcula-se o gradiente da funo.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}\nu_{1} - \nu_{3} - 2 x_{1} + 16\\\nu_{1} + \nu_{2} - \nu_{4} - 2 x_{2} + 16\\s_{1}^{2} + x_{1} + x_{2} - 10\\s_{2}^{2} + x_{2} - 5\\s_{3}^{2} - x_{1}\\s_{4}^{2} - x_{2}\\2 \nu_{1} s_{1}\\2 \nu_{2} s_{2}\\2 \nu_{3} s_{3}\\2 \nu_{4} s_{4}\end{matrix}\right]$

Existem 16 casos possveis para a soluo do problema. Destes, destacam-se os que so pontos candidatos, obedecendo o critrio de KKT.

$\displaystyle \left( \left[ \nu_{4}, \ s_{1}, \ s_{2}, \ s_{3}, \ x_{1}, \ x_{2}\right], \ \left\{\left( 16, \ \sqrt{2}, \ \sqrt{5}, \ 2 \sqrt{2}, \ 8, \ 0\right)\right\}\right)$
$\displaystyle \left( \left[ \nu_{3}, \ \nu_{4}, \ s_{1}, \ s_{2}, \ x_{1}, \ x_{2}\right], \ \left\{\left( 16, \ 16, \ \sqrt{10}, \ \sqrt{5}, \ 0, \ 0\right)\right\}\right)$
$\displaystyle \left( \left[ \nu_{1}, \ \nu_{4}, \ s_{2}, \ s_{3}, \ x_{1}, \ x_{2}\right], \ \left\{\left( 4, \ 20, \ \sqrt{5}, \ \sqrt{10}, \ 10, \ 0\right)\right\}\right)$

Problema 4.135¶

Check for convexity of the following function. If the function is not convex everywhere, than determine the domain (feasible set S)over which the function is convex.

\begin{align*} f(x_1,x_2) &= 3x_1^2+2x_1x_2+2x_2^2 +7\\ \end{align*}

O gradiente da funo, assim com a sua Hessiana, so calculados abaixo:

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}6 x_{1} + 2 x_{2}\\2 x_{1} + 4 x_{2}\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H = \left[\begin{matrix}6 & 2\\2 & 4\end{matrix}\right]$

Para checar a convexidade, calculam-se os autovalores da Hessiana.

$\displaystyle \lambda_1 = \left\{ 5 - \sqrt{5} : 1, \ \sqrt{5} + 5 : 1\right\}$

Como a Hessiana positivo definida, pode-se dizer que a funo convexa em todos os seus pontos.

Problema 4.136¶

Check for convexity of the following function. If the function is not convex everywhere, than determine the domain (feasible set S)over which the function is convex.

\begin{align*} f(x_1,x_2) &= x_1^2 + 4x_1x_2 + x_2^2 + 3\\ \end{align*}

O gradiente da funo, assim com a sua Hessiana, so calculados abaixo:

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}2 x_{1} + 4 x_{2}\\4 x_{1} + 2 x_{2}\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H = \left[\begin{matrix}2 & 4\\4 & 2\end{matrix}\right]$

Para checar a convexidade, calculam-se os autovalores da Hessiana.

$\displaystyle \lambda_1 = \left\{ -2 : 1, \ 6 : 1\right\}$

A Hessiana uma matriz indefinida, portanto, no possvel definir o domnio em que a funo f convexa.

Problema 4.140¶

Check for convexity of the following function. If the function is not convex everywhere, than determine the domain (feasible set S)over which the function is convex.

\begin{align*} U = \frac{21.9E7}{V^2C} + 3.9E6C + 1000V \end{align*}

Primeiramente, calcula-se o gradiente e a Hessiana da funo. Define-se V como $x_1$ e C como $x_2$.

$\displaystyle \nabla f(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}1000 - \frac{438000000.0}{x_{1}^{3} x_{2}}\\3900000.0 - \frac{219000000.0}{x_{1}^{2} x_{2}^{2}}\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H_ = \left[\begin{matrix}\frac{1314000000.0}{x_{1}^{4} x_{2}} & \frac{438000000.0}{x_{1}^{3} x_{2}^{2}}\\\frac{438000000.0}{x_{1}^{3} x_{2}^{2}} & \frac{438000000.0}{x_{1}^{2} x_{2}^{3}}\end{matrix}\right]$

Dividindo a Hessiana por $\dfrac{43.8E7}{x_1^4x_2^4}$,tem-se:

$\displaystyle H_ = \left[\begin{matrix}3.0 x_{2}^{3} & 1.0 x_{1} x_{2}^{2}\\1.0 x_{1} x_{2}^{2} & 1.0 x_{1}^{2} x_{2}\end{matrix}\right]$

Calculando os autovalores:

$\displaystyle \lambda = \left\{ 1.5 x_{2} \cdot \left(0.333333333333333 x_{1}^{2} + 1.0 x_{2}^{2}\right) - 1.5 x_{2} \sqrt{0.111111111111111 x_{1}^{4} - 0.222222222222222 x_{1}^{2} x_{2}^{2} + x_{2}^{4}} : 1, \ 1.5 x_{2} \cdot \left(0.333333333333333 x_{1}^{2} + 1.0 x_{2}^{2}\right) + 1.5 x_{2} \sqrt{0.111111111111111 x_{1}^{4} - 0.222222222222222 x_{1}^{2} x_{2}^{2} + x_{2}^{4}} : 1\right\}$

A partir dos autovalores, percebe-se que a Hessiana uma matriz positiva semidefinida, portanto a funo convexa para todo $x_2$ maior que zero

Problema 4.150¶

The problem of minimum weight design of the symmetric three-bar truss of Fig. 2.6 is formulated as follows:

\begin{align*} \mbox{Minimizar}\ f(x_1,x_2) = 2x_1 + x_2\\ \mbox{suj. a}\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left( \frac{P_u}{x_1} + \frac{P_v}{x_1 +\sqrt2 x_2}\right) - 20000 &\le 0 \\ \frac{\sqrt2 P_v}{x_1+\sqrt2 x_2} - 20000 &\le 0\\ -x_1 &\le 0\\ -x_2 &\le 0\\ \end{align*}

where x1 is the cross-sectional area of members 1 and 3 (symmetric structure) and x2 is the cross-sectional area of member 2, Pu = P cos u, Pv = P sin u, with P > 0 and 0 u 90. Check for convexity of the problem for u = 60 degree.

Para saber a convexidade da funo, analisam-se as restries do problema.

$\displaystyle \nabla g_1(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{0.707106781186547 P_{u}}{x_{1}^{2}} - \frac{0.353553390593274 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{2}}\\- \frac{0.5 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{2}}\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H_{g_1} = \left[\begin{matrix}\frac{1.41421356237309 P_{u}}{x_{1}^{3}} + \frac{0.5 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}} & \frac{0.707106781186547 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}}\\\frac{0.707106781186547 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}} & \frac{1.0 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}}\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle \nabla g_2(x) = \left[\begin{matrix}- \frac{0.707106781186547 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{2}}\\- \frac{1.0 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{2}}\end{matrix}\right]$
$\displaystyle H_{g_2} = \left[\begin{matrix}\frac{1.0 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}} & \frac{1.41421356237309 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}}\\\frac{1.41421356237309 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}} & \frac{2.0 P_{v}}{\left(0.707106781186547 x_{1} + x_{2}\right)^{3}}\end{matrix}\right]$

g1 e g2 so positivas semidefinidas, enquanto g3 e g4 so funes lineares. Com isso, pode-se afirmar que f uma funo convexa.
